# C++ Coding Style

## Braces

- **Always use braces** for `if`, `for`, `while`, `else`, etc. No single-line bodies without `{`.
- **Opening brace on a new line** (Allman style):

```cpp
// GOOD
if(x > 0)
{
    doSomething();
}

// BAD
if(x > 0) {
    doSomething();
}

// BAD
if(x > 0)
    doSomething();
```

## Reference & Pointer Symbols

`&`, `*`, and `&&` are adjacent to the **variable name**, not the type:

```cpp
// GOOD
int &x = y;
const Vector3D &point = getPoint();
int *ptr = &val;
T &&rval = std::move(obj);
void foo(const std::vector<int> &data);

// BAD
int& x = y;
int * ptr = &val;
```

## `auto`

Do **not** use `auto` unless it is genuinely needed (e.g. complex iterator types, lambda captures). Spell out the type explicitly.

## Line Length & Breaking

- Lines can be long. Do **not** add line breaks for nothing.
- Only break a line if it is **really** too long, and break at a reasonable location (after a comma, after an operator).
- No blank lines for no reason.

## Naming

- **Variables**: `camelCase` (`cellIndex`, `faceNeighbors`, `lowerLeft`).
- **Free functions**: start with a capital letter (`GetNeighbors`, `CalcFaceVelocity`).
- **Methods**: try to start with a capital letter as well (`BuildGrid`, `SetBox`).

## Keywords & Parentheses

No space between a keyword and its parenthesis:

```cpp
// GOOD
if(condition)
for(size_t i = 0; i < n; ++i)
while(running)
switch(val)

// BAD
if (condition)
for (size_t i = 0; i < n; ++i)
```
